After capturing NTLMv2 challenge-response hashes with Responder, the next step is offline password cracking.

This phase turns a captured authentication attempt into a usable credential if the password is weak enough. In an internal AD environment, that can quickly lead to:

share access
LDAP enumeration
BloodHound collection
remote login attempts
privilege escalation opportunities
Objective
Take captured NTLMv2 hashes from Responder
Verify the hash format
Crack them with Hashcat
Optionally test with John the Ripper
Validate recovered credentials safely in the lab
Tools Used
Kali Linux
Hashcat
John the Ripper (optional)
Responder log files
NetExec (nxc) for credential validation
Lab Environment
Attacker: Kali Linux
Target Type: Internal Active Directory lab
Sanitized Values:
Domain: LAB.LOCAL
User: labuser
Host: WORKSTATION01
DC: DC01
IPs: 192.168.x.x

All identifiers below are sanitized for public posting.

Attack Flow
Capture NTLMv2 hash with Responder
Extract the saved hash from the Responder logs
Save the hash to a crack file
Run Hashcat with the correct mode
Recover the password (if weak)
Validate credentials against lab services
Step 1 – Locate the Captured Hash

Responder saves captured authentication data here:

ls /usr/share/responder/logs

Example sanitized file names:

SMB-NTLMv2-SSP-[REDACTED].txt
HTTP-NTLMv2-[REDACTED].txt

Read the file:

cat /usr/share/responder/logs/SMB-NTLMv2-SSP-[REDACTED].txt
Step 2 – Confirm the NTLMv2 Format

A typical Responder NTLMv2 hash looks like this:

labuser::LAB:1122334455667788:AABBCCDDEEFF00112233445566778899:0101000000000000...
Important

For NTLMv2 challenge-response, keep the line exactly as captured.
Do not manually reformat it unless the tool specifically requires it.

Step 3 – Save the Hash to a File

Create a file for cracking:

nano ntlmv2_hashes.txt

Paste the captured line into the file, then save.

Quick check:

cat ntlmv2_hashes.txt
Step 4 – Crack with Hashcat (Primary Method)

For NTLMv2, the correct mode is:

5600

Run:

hashcat -m 5600 ntlmv2_hashes.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt
Step 5 – View Cracked Results

If Hashcat succeeds:

hashcat -m 5600 ntlmv2_hashes.txt --show

Example sanitized output:

labuser::LAB:1122334455667788:AABBCCDDEEFF00112233445566778899:0101000000000000...:Password123!
Step 6 – Optional: Use John the Ripper

Alternative method:

john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt ntlmv2_hashes.txt

Show results:

john --show ntlmv2_hashes.txt
Why Hashcat Is Usually Preferred

For this phase, Hashcat is usually stronger because:

faster on supported hardware
better control over rules / masks
easier to scale later
common in password auditing workflows
Common Issues
1. Wrong Hash Mode

If you use the wrong mode, cracking will fail.

For Responder NTLMv2, use:

-m 5600
2. Bad Hash Formatting

Do not break the hash into multiple lines.
Do not remove the :: structure.

Keep the full line intact:

user::DOMAIN:challenge:response:blob
3. Empty / Invalid File

Check the file:

cat ntlmv2_hashes.txt
wc -l ntlmv2_hashes.txt
4. rockyou.txt Missing

If needed:

ls /usr/share/wordlists

If compressed:

sudo gzip -d /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt.gz
Step 7 – Validate Recovered Credentials

Once a password is recovered, test it carefully in the lab.

SMB Validation
nxc smb 192.168.x.x -u labuser -p 'Password123!' -d LAB.LOCAL
LDAP Validation
nxc ldap 192.168.x.x -u labuser -p 'Password123!' -d LAB.LOCAL
WinRM Validation (if applicable)
nxc winrm 192.168.x.x -u labuser -p 'Password123!' -d LAB.LOCAL
What a Successful Validation May Show

Possible output:

SMB  192.168.x.x  445  DC01  [+] LAB.LOCAL\labuser:Password123!

This confirms:

the password is valid
the account is usable
the credential can support the next attack stage
Security Impact

A cracked NTLMv2 hash can quickly become:

valid domain credentials
SMB share access
LDAP enumeration access
BloodHound data collection
remote management testing
a bridge into post-compromise activity

This is why weak passwords make internal auth exposure far more dangerous.

Detection Ideas

Blue teams should watch for:

unusual authentication failures followed by successful login
suspicious SMB / LDAP enumeration shortly after credential exposure
password spray / validation patterns
offline cracking cannot be directly seen, but follow-on usage can

Good telemetry after a crack:

new SMB sessions
unexpected LDAP binds
unusual WinRM usage
auth to servers the user normally does not access
MITRE ATT&CK Mapping
T1110.002 – Password Cracking
T1078 – Valid Accounts
T1021.002 – SMB/Windows Admin Shares (follow-on)
T1087 – Account Discovery (follow-on)
Defensive Controls
Enforce longer passwords / passphrases
Reduce NTLM usage where possible
Disable LLMNR / NBT-NS to prevent initial capture
Monitor suspicious internal authentication patterns
Limit where standard users can authenticate
Apply MFA where feasible for administrative workflows
Public Posting Safety

Before pushing to GitHub:

redact full hashes
hide real usernames
replace real domains with LAB.LOCAL
replace hostnames with DC01, WORKSTATION01
replace IPs with 192.168.x.x
do not post real cracked passwords from non-lab systems
Good Public Replacements
LAB.LOCAL
labuser
Password123!
192.168.x.x
[REDACTED_HASH]
